The [[Sicels|Sicel]] city the Romans called '''Assorus''' (Greek '''Assoros''') is the modern '''[[Assoro]]''' in the province of [[Enna]], Sicily.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462106 |title=Places: 462106 (Assorus) |author=Wilson, R. |author2 =DARMC |author3 =R. Talbert |author4 =V. Vitale |author5 =J. Becker |author6 =S. Gillies |author7 =J. Prag |author8 =T. Elliott |accessdate=November 13, 2015 <!-- 4:18 pm -->  |publisher=Pleiades}}</ref> Assorus was an inland town, midway between Enna and Agyrium. It long resisted Hellenization, and retained its traditional Sicel character.<ref>[http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0060.tlg001.perseus-eng1:14.58 Diodorus Siculus 14.58]</ref> [[Marcus Tullius Cicero|Cicero]] refers to the site in his [[Verrines|Verrine orations.]]<ref>[http://latin.packhum.org/loc/474/5/184/80-85,207-212,338-343,432-437 Marcus Tullius Cicero, ''In Verrem'' 2.4.96.1, 2.4.96.4, 2.4.96.6, 2.4.96.7]</ref>

